Metaphysics is the study of questions that cannot be answered directly through perception by means of rational reasoning and logic. Metaphysics is the fundamental law of philosophy that aims to explain the basic nature of existence and the world. The Chinese translation of "metaphysics" is taken from the phrase "Those who are above in form are called the Way, those who are below in form are called the Weapon" in the I Ching (Yijing), which was translated from metaphysic by the Japanese Tetsujiro Inoue (Meiji era). (Meiji era). The branch of metaphysics includes ontology, natural theology and its extensions. Ontology is "the study of which nouns represent real entities of existence and which nouns represent only concepts. Metaphysical naturalism is the denial of the existence of God. It is based on the idea that all phenomena can be explained by the concept of natural reasons, and is proposed by philosophers who support science and evolutionary theory. Methodological naturalism, on the other hand, refers to an approach to the study of God that does not say anything about God. Philosophy of mind is the branch of philosophy that studies the nature of consciousness and their relationship with the physical body (especially the brain). Dualism and monism are the two main schools of thought that discuss the "relationship between mind and body". Epistemology is a branch of philosophy that explores the nature, origin, and scope of knowledge. Ethics is the discipline of systematic reflection and study of human moral life; here, morality is defined as all codes of behavior recognized by a group of people or a culture. It is mainly divided into metaethics (the study of the nature of ethical theory or criticism in the abstract), normative ethics (the critique of different moral views and the giving of moral code recommendations for right or wrong behavior. It studies the style of moral behavior that people should follow, applied ethics, which applies ethical theories to real-life situations, including bioethics and political ethics, and descriptive ethics, which gathers information about how people live and summarizes it from observed patterns. It examines ethics not in terms of preconceived theories but in terms of the real choices made and observed by actual moral agents, all the moral factors that contribute to those choices, and the ethical views held by social groups. The history of ethics includes Greco-Roman ethics and medieval Christian ethics. Part I: Humanist ethical thought, represented by Walla and Montaigne and others. Part II: The ethical thought of the Reformation, represented by Calvin. The third part: ethics of politics, represented by Machiavelli and others, modern ethics (17th-18th centuries, British empiricist ethics, represented by Hume and others, 17th-18th centuries, continental rationalist ethics, represented by Spinoza and others, 18th centuries, French Enlightenment ethics, represented by Voltaire and others, 18th-19th centuries, German academic ethics, represented by (Kant and Hegel, etc.), 18th-19th century, British utilitarian ethics (Bianchin and Sidgwick, etc.), 19th century, British evolutionary ethics (Spencer and Huxley, etc.), late 19th century, German neo-Kantian ethics (Li Keil, etc.), late 19th century, neo-Hegelian ethics (Thomas Hill Green, etc.), and transitional ethics (Kant and Hegel, etc.). In the late 19th century, neo-Hegelian ethics, represented by Thomas Hill Green, etc.), and transitional ethics (irrationalist ethics, represented by Kierkegaard, Schopenhauer and Nietzsche, etc.). Logic is the study of "principles and criteria of valid inference and proof". Logic usually consists of three parts: inductive reasoning, retrospective reasoning and deductive reasoning, and can be divided into formal and non-formal logic. Aesthetics is a discipline that focuses on the study of the nature of beauty and its meaning.
